svg.desc:
SIMPLE PANTHER AND BIRD FRAME BY FRAME ANIMATION Coded by Emasoft for Opentoonz (https://github.com/opentoonz/opentoonz)
Example implementation of basic SVG frame-by-frame animation, for educational purpouses. A frame based animation is easy to export. No javascript or CSS, just pure SVG. In this way the SVG format is used like an MPEG for vector animations.
This animation has two animation groups: - the panther (17 frames, 0.75s per frame) - the bird (9 frames, 0.75s per frame)
Usually they would be joined in a single frame sequence. But to show the flexibility of this method, since the cycle of the bird is shorter than the cycle of the panther, we are going to treat them as separate entities standing on the same animation scene. In this way we reduce both the svg file size and the ram used during playback. For small entities like those two it would seem nothing much, but when bigger elements with thousands of vectors are used in more realistic scenarios, the gains become evident.
This file is divided in two sections:
1) The Definitions (defs) : Here you need to put all frames and clipping paths. All frames require an unique id. For example: frame0001, frame0002, etc. All elements of a frame must be wrapped in a group with such id or, if needed to reduce memory consumption, a frame can be broken into different parts, with different amount of frames for each element. In such case, the ids can be named with the sub element name followed by the frame number (e.g. bird_0001). Objects written here are not displayed until the animation cycle instances them.
2) The Animation Scene (a group called "animation_scene") : Here you need to put the elements on the scene. First the background rectangle (with or without a clipping path), then the animated groups of objects (one called "animated_group_1" and the other called "animated_group_2"). The animation elements needs the following parameters:
values : the id of the frames, with a leading # char and separated by a ; char. The frames must be named in the exact order you need them to be displayed. Also the first frame id must be indicated in the "use" element as the href (example: xlink:href="#frame0001" ).
begin : the start time delay, in seconds (example: 0s).
repeatCount : this should set on "indefinite" if you want a looping animation. Otherwise on "0" if you want the animation to stop at the last frame. Any other number would be the number of repetitions of the entire sequence.
dur : the duration in seconds of each frame. For example: "1.0" means 1 frame per second. For 60fps is "0.01667". For 24fps you have "0.04167" seconds. (just divide 1 for the number of frames, i.e. 1/60=0.0166666.., aprox: "0.01667").
Please refer to Opentoonz repository on GitHub for any error/issue/question. Enjoy.
